mesenteric lymph nodes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoeliac lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary lymphatic drainage site for all foregut structures. These nodes are located around the coeliac trunk and receive lymph from the distal oesophagus, stomach, proximal duodenum (up to the major duodenal papilla), liver, gallbladder, and pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPara-aortic lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E receive drainage from retroperitoneal structures and the lower limbs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior mesenteric lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E drain the midgut structures from the major duodenal papilla to the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThoracic duct directly\u003C/strong\u003E receives lymph from the cisterna chyli rather than directly from foregut structures\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior mesenteric lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E drain the hindgut structures from the distal third of the transverse colon to the upper anal canal\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe coeliac lymph nodes ultimately drain into the cisterna chyli, which then empties into the thoracic duct.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The coeliac lymph nodes receive lymphatic drainage from foregut structures including the distal oesophagus, stomach, proximal duodenum, liver, gallbladder, and pancreas.","The foregut extends from the distal oesophagus to the second part of the duodenum at the major duodenal papilla.","The coeliac lymph nodes are located around the coeliac trunk and drain into the cisterna chyli."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"da